### 3.1 Parameter Robustness Test

To test whether the observed signal depends sensitively on specific coefficient choices, a robustness sweep was performed in which the primary accumulation, smoothing, amplification, and clipping parameters were substantially perturbed while keeping the overall model structure unchanged.

The following parameters were varied simultaneously:

accumulation decay scale (τ)
structure exponent
smoothing scales
amplification scaling
global history-field scaling
positive and negative clipping limits

These perturbations altered the detailed construction of the history field while preserving the underlying accumulation framework.

Despite these substantial modifications, the overall statistical behaviour of the model remained remarkably stable across the SPARC sample:

Median ΔBIC remained near zero
The positive-fit fraction remained near 45%
The same dominant high-ΔBIC galaxies consistently reappeared
Large improvements persisted with similar order-of-magnitude strength

In particular, NGC 2403, UGC 11914, and NGC 6015 remained the strongest-performing galaxies under the perturbed parameter configuration.

This robustness suggests that the observed signal is not solely dependent on narrowly fine-tuned coefficient choices, but instead reflects a more stable structural relationship within the accumulation framework itself.

### 3.2 Predictive Validation Test

To test whether the history-accumulation framework possesses predictive capability beyond descriptive fitting, a blind predictive validation experiment was performed across the SPARC sample.

For each galaxy:

* the inner 70% of radial data points were used as the fitting region,
* the outer 30% of the rotation curve was withheld from fitting,
* halo parameters were optimized only on the inner region,
* and the frozen history-accumulation model was then used to predict the unseen outer rotation behaviour.

No galaxy-specific retuning or post-fit adjustment was performed after the hidden regions were revealed.

The predictive comparison was evaluated using the difference in prediction-region χ²:

Δprediction​=χbaseline2​−χhistory

Positive values therefore indicate improved prediction of the unseen outer rotation curve by the history-accumulation model relative to the baseline Burkert halo fit.

